# 🐧 Linux Theory

## What is Archiving?

Archiving is the process of combining multiple files and directories into a single file.

An archive helps organize files and simplifies backups and file transfers.

The most common Linux archiving tool is **tar (Tape Archive)**.

Example:

Documents/

Photos/

Logs/

↓

backup.tar

---

## What is Compression?

Compression reduces the size of a file to save storage space and reduce transfer time.

Unlike archiving, compression focuses on reducing file size.

Common compression formats include:

- gzip (.gz)
- zip (.zip)
- bzip2 (.bz2)

---

## Difference Between Archiving and Compression

| Archiving | Compression |
|------------|-------------|
| Combines multiple files | Reduces file size |
| Uses tar | Uses gzip, zip |
| Does not reduce size | Reduces size |

These processes are commonly used together.

Example:

Project Folder

↓

project.tar

↓

project.tar.gz

---

## Why Administrators Compress Files

System administrators compress files because:

- Saves disk space
- Faster file transfers
- Easier backups
- Simplifies sharing multiple files
- Preserves directory structure

---

## Common Linux Commands

Create archive

```bash
tar -cvf backup.tar folder/
```

View archive

```bash
tar -tvf backup.tar
```

Extract archive

```bash
tar -xvf backup.tar
```

Compress archive

```bash
gzip backup.tar
```

Extract compressed archive

```bash
gunzip backup.tar.gz
```

Create ZIP archive

```bash
zip backup.zip *.txt
```

Extract ZIP archive

```bash
unzip backup.zip
```

