# 🌐 Networking Theory

## What is a Port?

A port is a logical communication endpoint used by applications to send and receive network traffic.

An IP address identifies a device.

A port identifies the application running on that device.

Example

Computer IP

192.168.1.20

Applications

- Web Browser
- Email Client
- SSH
- DNS

Each application communicates using different ports.

---

## Why Ports are Required

Without ports, a computer would not know which application should receive incoming network traffic.

Ports allow multiple applications to use the network simultaneously.

---

## Common Port Numbers

| Port | Protocol | Service |
|-------|----------|----------|
|20|TCP|FTP Data|
|21|TCP|FTP Control|
|22|TCP|SSH|
|23|TCP|Telnet|
|25|TCP|SMTP|
|53|TCP/UDP|DNS|
|67|UDP|DHCP Server|
|68|UDP|DHCP Client|
|80|TCP|HTTP|
|110|TCP|POP3|
|143|TCP|IMAP|
|443|TCP|HTTPS|
|3389|TCP|Remote Desktop|

---

## TCP vs UDP Review

TCP

- Connection-oriented
- Reliable
- Error checking
- Slower

Examples

SSH

HTTP

HTTPS

FTP

---

UDP

- Connectionless
- Faster
- No error checking
- Lower overhead

Examples

DNS

DHCP

VoIP

Streaming

